      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Originalism provides a clear, stable foundation because it anchors constitutional meaning to the text and historical understanding at the time of ratification. The \"living constitution\" approach, however, is fundamentally subjective, allowing judges to adapt the law to contemporary social or political pressures. A truly objective view recognizes that while originalism offers stability, it can also be rigid and fail to address evolving societal realities. Therefore, the strength of the originalist view lies in its commitment to textual fidelity, which is a powerful legal principle.",
      "source": "target",
